-- Baoshan Steel, Minsheng Banking, Vanke: China Equity Preview
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2010-09-30T00:31:18Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-29/vanke-baosteel-ningbo-bank-jiaozuo-wanfang-china-equity-market-preview.html
The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in China trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and share prices are as of the last close.  The  Shanghai Composite Index , which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, dropped 0.68, or less than 0.1 percent,
to 2,610.68. The  CSI 300 Index  fell 0.2 percent to 2,874.81.
Chinese markets will be closed from tomorrow to Oct. 7 for
National Day holidays.  Developers: China will speed up the introduction of a trial
property tax in some cities and then expand the levy to the
whole country to curb rising real estate prices, the government
said, without giving a timetable.  China Vanke Co.  (000002 CH), the nation’s largest real
estate developer, fell 1 percent to 7.81 yuan. Poly Real Estate
Group Co. (600048 CH), the second biggest, added 1.4 percent to
11.35 yuan.  Steel producers: China’s steel production is expected to
fall until the end of this year, boosting prices, China National
Radio reported, citing a government report. The output declines
are due to power restrictions, it said.  Baoshan Iron & Steel Co.  (600019 CH), the listed unit of
China’s second-biggest steelmaker, rose 1.2 percent to 6.54 yuan.
Hebei Iron & Steel Co. (000709 CH), the listed unit of China’s
biggest steelmaker, dropped 0.3 percent to 3.82 yuan.  Aluminum Corp. of China Ltd.  (601600 CH): The company said
parent Aluminum Corp. of China will gain control of Jiangxi Rare
Earth & Rare Metals Tungsten Group Corp. by way of a capital
increase and new share subscription. Aluminum Corp. of China
Ltd., the listed unit of nation’s biggest maker of the
lightweight metal and also called Chalco, jumped 7.5 percent to
11.70 yuan.  Bank of Ningbo Co.  (002142 CH): The bank that’s part-owned
by Singapore’s Oversea-Chinese Banking Corp. said it has won
approval from the China Banking Regulatory Commission to
establish a branch in the eastern city of Wuxi. The stock fell
0.3 percent to 11.59 yuan.  China Minsheng Banking Corp.  (600016 CH): The nation’s
first privately owned bank said its financial leasing unit plans
to issue 1.895 billion new shares in a private share placement.
The stock added 0.8 percent to 5.01 yuan.  Citic Securities Co.  (600030 CH): China’s biggest listed
brokerage may open its first wholly owned offshore subsidiary in
Australia to do business with Chinese companies seeking
acquisitions of mining resources, the Wall Street Journal
reported, citing a person familiar with the situation. The stock
dropped 1 percent to 10.52 yuan.  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China Ltd.  (601398 CH):
Goldman Sachs Group Inc. raised $2.25 billion from selling
shares in ICBC in Hong Kong. Goldman Sachs sold 3.04 billion
existing shares in ICBC at HK$5.74 each, according to a sale
document sent to fund managers. ICBC, the nation’s biggest
listed lender, rose 0.3 percent to 4.01 yuan.  Liaoning Huajin Tongda Chemicals Co.  (000059 CH): The
fertilizer manufacturer and Angola’s Sonangol SA have reached an
initial agreement to establish a joint venture, the Chinese
company said in a statement to the stock exchange. The shares
rose 1.9 percent to 10.39 yuan.  -- Zhang Shidong ,  Winnie Zhu . Editor:  Glenn J. Kalinoski   To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
